    "content": "**Geopolitiks Snacks** - May 13, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🛢️ Trump brought Hormuz to Beijing in his carry-on\n\nThe China trip is officially about great-power choreography. Unofficially, oil markets are holding the cue cards.\n\n- **The summit:** AP says Trump headed to Beijing while downplaying differences with Xi Jinping over the Iran war and the blocked Strait of Hormuz.\n- **The leverage:** China remains the biggest buyer of Iranian oil, while Washington wants Beijing to pressure Tehran into accepting U.S. terms and reopening the route.\n- **The market:** Reuters says Brent fell to $106.30, but prices remain around triple digits after the U.S.-Israel war and Tehran's Hormuz shutdown.\n\n*The diplomatic agenda says trade. The barrel price says otherwise.*\n\n**Sources:** [AP](https://apnews.com/article/trump-xi-iran-sanctions-trade-48b0ca751712ce473ffcd207997928af) | [Reuters via Investing.com](https://au.investing.com/news/commodities-news/oil-prices-slip-on-teetering-iran-ceasefire-as-trump-heads-to-china-4429447)\n\n---\n\n## 🚀 Russia ended the ceasefire with a drone receipt\n\nThe 72-hour pause survived just long enough to be described in past tense, which is about the going rate for this war.\n\n- **The attack:** Reuters says Russia launched more than 200 drones at Ukraine overnight after the U.S.-mediated ceasefire expired.\n- **The casualties:** Ukrainian officials reported attacks on civilian infrastructure, including a kindergarten, with at least one person killed and six injured.\n- **The diplomacy:** Kyiv said it proposed extending the truce beyond May 11, while Moscow accused Ukraine of repeated violations during the pause.\n\n*The prisoner-swap optics were nice. The air-defense alerts were louder.*\n\n**Sources:** [Reuters via KELO](https://kelo.com/2026/05/12/russia-strikes-ukraine-with-drones-as-ceasefire-ends-ukrainian-officials-say/) | [AP via ABC News](https://abcnews.com/International/wireStory/russia-ukraine-trade-blame-continued-fighting-us-brokered-132839834)\n\n---\n\n## 🚢 Gaza's flotilla fight moved to deportation paperwork\n\nThe blockade drama now comes with court hearings, diplomatic condemnations and the usual argument over who gets to call it security.\n\n- **The deportations:** AP says Israel deported Saif Abukeshek and Thiago Ávila, two Global Sumud Flotilla steering-committee members, after holding them for just over a week.\n- **The interception:** Israeli forces stopped 22 boats carrying 175 activists hundreds of miles from Gaza, according to activists cited by AP.\n- **The reaction:** Spain and Brazil condemned the detention of their citizens, while Israel said it would not allow a breach of the naval blockade.\n\n*Humanitarian access remains easy to invoke, hard to sail toward.*\n\n**Sources:** [AP](https://apnews.com/article/israel-gaza-flotilla-activists-sumud-avila-53936bb09dbd84e29f92c6be7ab8397f)\n"
  }
]
